{"text": "(4.12)\n\nand conclude that k\u27e9is an eigenstate of \u02c6D with an eigenvalue e\u2212ik. Note that the number of independent eigenstates\n\nis N. For exmaple for a 5-site system we have eik6 = eik1.\n\n====== [4.4] Momentum operator\n\nThe momentum operator is defined as follows:\n\n\u02c6p k\u27e9\n\n\u2261\n\nk k\u27e9\n\n(4.13)\n\nFrom the relation \u02c6D k\u27e9= e\u2212ik k\u27e9it follows that \u02c6D k\u27e9= e\u2212i\u02c6p k\u27e9. Therefore we deduce the operator identity:\n\n\u02c6D\n\n=\n\ne\u2212i\u02c6p\n\n(4.14)\n\nWe can also define 2-step, 3-step, and a-step translation operators as follows:\n\n\u02c6D(2)\n\n=\n\n( \u02c6D)2\n\n=\n\ne\u2212i2\u02c6p\n\n(4.15)\n\n\u02c6D(3)\n\n=\n\n( \u02c6D)3\n\n=\n\ne\u2212i3\u02c6p\n\n\u02c6D(a)\n\n=\n\n( \u02c6D)a\n\n=\n\ne\u2212ia\u02c6p\n\n21\n\n[5] The continuum limit\n\n====== [5.1] Definition of the Wave Function\n\nBelow we will consider a site system in the continuum limit. \u03b5 \u21920 is the distance between the sites, and L is the length\n\nof the system. So, the number of sites is N = L/\u03b5 \u2192\u221e. The eigenvalues of the position operator are xi = \u03b5 \u00d7 integer.\n\nWe use the following recipe for changing a sum into an integral:\n\nX\n\ni\n\n7\u2192\n\nZ dx\n\n\u03b5\n\n(5.1) 2> 1>\n\nThe definition of the position operator is:\n\n\u02c6x xi\u27e9= xi xi\u27e9\n\n(5.2)\n\nThe completeness of the basis can be written as follows\n\n1\n\n=\n\nX xi\u27e9\u27e8xi =\n\nZ x\u27e9dx\u27e8x (5.3)\n\nIn order to get rid of the \u03b5 in the integration measure we have re-defined the normalization of the basis states as\n\nfollows: x\u27e9=\n\n1\n\n\u221a\u03b5 xi\u27e9\n\n[infinite norm!]\n\n(5.4)\n\nAccordingly the orthonormality relation takes the following form,\n\n\u27e8x x\u2032\u27e9\n\n=\n\n\u03b4(x \u2212x\u2032)\n\n(5.5)\n\nwhere the Dirac delta function is defined as \u03b4(0) = 1/\u03b5 and zero otherwise. Consequently the representation of a\n\nquantum state is: \u03c8\u27e9\n\n=\n\nX\n\ni\n\n\u03c8i xi\u27e9\n\n=\n\nZ\n\ndx \u03c8(x) x\u27e9\n\n(5.6)\n\nwhere\n\n\u03c8(x)\n\n\u2261\n\n\u27e8x \u03c8\u27e9\n\n=\n\n1\n\n\u221a\u03b5\u03c8x\n\n(5.7)\n\nNote the normalization of the \u201dwave function\u201d is:\n\n\u27e8\u03c8 \u03c8\u27e9\n\n=\n\nX\n\nx \u03c8x 2\n\n=\n\nZ dx\n\n\u03b5 \u03c8x 2\n\n=\n\nZ\n\ndx \u03c8(x)", "embedding": [-0.009285827, -0.014232795, 0.039900266, -0.015084502, 0.0071466034, -0.016942458, 0.0016878349, 0.012462259, -0.064342506, 0.06642757, 0.074706, 0.0012955909, -0.021541087, -0.02338753, -0.01683129, 0.033405755, -0.036126148, 0.00040764557, -0.06501773, 0.012742245, 0.041792657, -0.0029451863, -0.101745345, -0.006027144, -0.039386816, 0.018873196, 0.04379872, 0.025096284, 0.06107331, 0.052494302, 0.04176507, -0.022846567, 0.04082926, -0.038316514, 0.0066697216, 0.029998172, 0.0040215515, -0.019655345, 0.02036019, -0.035912838, 0.034770165, 0.008288822, 0.023233071, -0.0011668188, -0.061870378, -0.03339244, -0.020102201, -0.0019599686, -0.02960309, -0.06390697, 0.020076714, -0.0010613359, 0.038916815, -0.027074728, -0.011245119, 0.010292144, 0.034436792, 0.02966223, -0.00239691, 0.025463536, 0.017638125, -0.0031616082, 0.0238202, -0.039651673, 0.018687075, 0.013674834, -0.036640424, 0.027121693, 0.03054979, -0.046322666, -0.008775622, -0.016883647, -0.04475493, -0.0045724814, -0.03257902, 0.0474602, -0.03611236, -0.010703805, -0.08589865, -0.012748203, -0.011157853, -0.02214943, -0.0032142673, 0.0053413343, -0.034407858, 0.0024004108, -0.0031308383, -0.025367323, 0.00355371, -0.012258499, 0.021315863, 0.063789696, 0.001751841, 0.007585308, 0.0254833, 0.043030933, 0.032722563, 0.01914597, 0.05115452, 0.0013609829, 0.033293072, 0.035551637, -0.019287776, 0.06662438, -0.01081676, 0.04467741, -0.0069683036, 0.027417842, 0.013413883, -0.05461143, 0.03888586, -0.008061418, 0.013997289, 0.020298911, -0.03777606, 0.032642245, 0.03268013, 0.004654541, -0.019650796, -0.0064401478, 0.021582734, 0.016603542,